<subSubSection id="1FE5655FFFFC4170CAD1EEB9FDA52258" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="462" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="574036D4FFFC4171CAD1EEB9FAAD2795" blockId="10.[151,1311,2005,2032]" box="[151,1311,2005,2032]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFC4171CAD1EEB9FE91278A" bold="true" box="[151,291,2005,2031]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">References:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFFC4171CB6CEEBAFD882795" author="Conti, E. &amp; Viglianisi, F. M." box="[298,570,2005,2032]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" pagination="261 - 269" refId="ref15939" refString="Conti, E. &amp; Viglianisi, F. M. (2005) Ecology of the calling song of two Namibian armoured ground crickets, Acanthoplus longipes and Acanthoproctus diadematus (Orthoptera Tettigoniidae Hetrodinae). Ethology, Ecology &amp; Evolution, 17, 261 - 269. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 08927014.2005.9522596" type="journal article" year="2005">Conti &amp; Viglianisi 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFFC4171C803EEBAFC1F2795" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[581,941,2006,2032]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" pagination="29 - 35" refId="ref17489" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2011) Temporal patterns of intra- and interspecific acoustic signals differ in two closely related species of Acanthoplus (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae). Zoology, 114, 29 - 35. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. zool. 2010.09.002" type="journal article" year="2011">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFFC4171C9FEEEBAFAAD2795" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[952,1311,2006,2032]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" pagination="204 - 216" refId="ref17547" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2013) The acoustic communication system in six species of armoured ground crickets (Orthop- tera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae): commonalities and species-specific differences. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 252, 204 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2012.05.005" type="journal article" year="2013">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2013</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFFD4170CA81E9FAFDA52258" blockId="11.[151,1436,150,573]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170CA81E9FAFED020D5" bold="true" box="[199,354,150,176]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170CB2FE9FBFDE820D4" baseAuthorityName="Charpentier" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[361,602,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170CB2FE9FBFDE820D4" box="[361,602,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Acanthoplus longipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170C8C9E9FBFC9520D4" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[655,807,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discoidalis">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170C8C9E9FBFC9520D4" box="[655,807,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">A. discoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possess stridulatory files with unusually few teeth (fewer only in 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170CB56E9D7FDBF20B0" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[272,525,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Anepisceptus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horridus">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170CB56E9D7FDBF20B0" box="[272,525,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Anepisceptus horridus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and quite large intervals between the teeth. Their calling songs look relatively complicated because they consist of two groups of impulses which are repeated again and again resulting in a trilllike structure (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFFD4170CB7AE86FFE302178" box="[316,386,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,632,1736]" captionTargetId="figure-221@11.[151,1436,597,1753]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Acanthoplus, Gymnoproctus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes (figures of Acanthoplus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Acanthoplus discoidalis, B–C Acanthoplus longipes, D Gymnoproctus rammei, E Gymnoproctus sculpturatus, F Gymnoproctus spec., G Acanthoproctus cervinus, H Acanthoproctus diadematus, I Hetrodes pupus. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-mssection)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392729/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
; based on data and figures taken from literature). In our interpretation, both groups together should be considered as one syllable produced during one closing movement with a short break in the middle (e.g., in 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170CAF2E827FEC22100" authorityName="Heller, K. -G. &amp; F. M. H. Willemse" authorityYear="1989" box="[180,368,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Leptophyes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lisae">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170CAF2E827FEC22100" box="[180,368,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Leptophyes lisae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFFD4170CB39E827FDBA2100" author="Heller, K. - G." box="[383,520,331,357]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" refId="ref16647" refString="Heller, K. - G. (1988) Bioakustik der europaischen Laubheuschrecken. Okologie in Forschung und Anwendung, Bd. 1. Verlag J. Margraf, Weikersheim, 358 pp." type="book" year="1988">Heller 1988</bibRefCitation>
). This idea is supported by the observation that in the first group the impulses are typically increasing in amplitude and in the second decreasing (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFFD4170C919E803FC1621EC" box="[863,932,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,632,1736]" captionTargetId="figure-221@11.[151,1436,597,1753]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Acanthoplus, Gymnoproctus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes (figures of Acanthoplus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Acanthoplus discoidalis, B–C Acanthoplus longipes, D Gymnoproctus rammei, E Gymnoproctus sculpturatus, F Gymnoproctus spec., G Acanthoproctus cervinus, H Acanthoproctus diadematus, I Hetrodes pupus. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-mssection)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392729/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
; not the case only in 7C). Both species differ distinctly in the syllable repetition rate with 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170C8CAE8FFFCB921C8" baseAuthorityName="Charpentier" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[652,779,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170C8CAE8FFFCB921C8" box="[652,779,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">A. longipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
singing faster than 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170C9ADE8FFFB3621C8" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1003,1156,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discoidalis">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170C9ADE8FFFB3621C8" box="[1003,1156,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">A. discoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The differences in SRR between the two recordings of 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170C844E8DBFD2F21B4" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[514,669,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discoidalis">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170C844E8DBFD2F21B4" box="[514,669,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">A. discoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFFD4170C8F6E8DBFC7E21B4" author="Conti, E. &amp; Viglianisi, F. M." box="[688,972,438,465]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" pagination="261 - 269" refId="ref15939" refString="Conti, E. &amp; Viglianisi, F. M. (2005) Ecology of the calling song of two Namibian armoured ground crickets, Acanthoplus longipes and Acanthoproctus diadematus (Orthoptera Tettigoniidae Hetrodinae). Ethology, Ecology &amp; Evolution, 17, 261 - 269. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 08927014.2005.9522596" type="journal article" year="2005">Conti &amp; Viglianisi 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFFD4170C99CE8DBFAFE21B4" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[986,1356,439,465]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" pagination="204 - 216" refId="ref17547" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2013) The acoustic communication system in six species of armoured ground crickets (Orthop- tera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae): commonalities and species-specific differences. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 252, 204 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2012.05.005" type="journal article" year="2013">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2013</bibRefCitation>
) result very probably from the different temperatures during recording. 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170C93DE8B7FC4E2190" baseAuthorityName="Charpentier" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[891,1020,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170C93DE8B7FC4E2190" box="[891,1020,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">A. longipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females made phonotaxis mainly to the species-specific song pattern, while 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFFD4170C81AE893FD47227C" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[604,757,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discoidalis">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFFD4170C81AE893FD47227C" box="[604,757,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">A. discoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females were attracted to a wider spectrum of song models (
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFFD4170CAD9EB4FFDB92258" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[159,523,547,573]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" pagination="29 - 35" refId="ref17489" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2011) Temporal patterns of intra- and interspecific acoustic signals differ in two closely related species of Acanthoplus (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae). Zoology, 114, 29 - 35. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. zool. 2010.09.002" type="journal article" year="2011">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
